Cow milk is a carbon source consisted of various constituents with different chemical properties, including polarity. So, there is some reason to deduce that the CMCDs obtained were of different surface polarities. Herein, ethyl acetate, which is a solvent with relatively cheap price and low toxicity, was used to extract CMCDs. The fraction extracted in ethyl acetate is best described as amphiphilic due to the simultaneous presence of hydrophobic moieties (CH, COC) and hydrophilic functional groups (OH, NH), judging from the IR spectra (Fig. 2
                        ) [13]. In other words, the amphiphilic CMCDs (ACMCDs) hold less surface-polarity than that of the hydrophilic ones which remain in the aqueous phase. Furthermore, TEM images (Fig. 3
                        ) show that the two fractions have similar narrow size distributions and morphologies, which indicates that the extraction had no significant effect on the morphology of CMCDs.

Due to their compatibility with organic solvent, ACMCDs can be easily doped into polymer to make nanocomposite thin films [24]. Here we show the fabrication of antibacterial thin films based on ACMCD-Ag nanocomposite which was prepared by using ACMCDs as both a reducing agent and a template. The synthetic flow chart of ACMCD-Ag as a function of UV irradiation time is shown in Fig. S3. Increasing the UV irradiation time changed the color of the mixed solution of AgNO3 and ACMCDs from slight yellow to dark brown, which showed the reaction occurred [20]. The absorption spectra of ACMCDs and ACMCD-Ag are shown in Fig. 4
                        . It could be seen that an absorption band with a maximum at 430nm arose after the photochemical reaction, which corresponded well with the spectral behavior of silver nanoparticles [25]. The TEM images further indicated the successful formation of the ACMCD-Ag (Fig. 5
                        ). The ACMCD-Ag had average diameters and distinguishing lattice fringes of ∼4nm and 0.206nm for the ACMCDs and ∼6nm and 0.236nm for the Ag nanoparticles, respectively [26].

The antibacterial properties of ACMCD-Ag against Gram-negative (E. coli) and Gram-positive (S. aureus) bacteria were confirmed using minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) test and Kirby–Bauer disk diffusion method [27]. AgNO3 was used as a model compound for the comparison of activity. As shown in Fig. 6a–d, the disks with ACMCD-Ag were surrounded by a larger diameter of inhibition zone compared to AgNO3 for both E. coli and S. aureus strains. The MIC of ACMCD-Ag was lower than that of AgNO3 for 24h incubation (Table 1
                        ). Thus, ACMCD-Ag has superior antimicrobial property compared with AgNO3 at the same Ag concentration. AgNO3 released Ag+ ions as the antimicrobial agent, but the diffusion of silver ions might be blocked by the formation of secondary compounds such as AgCl in the cultivate medium. In the case of ACMCD-Ag, the silver nanoparticles could freely diffuse into the cultivate media and act as biocidal agents. Therefore, the synthesized nanocomposite showed a superior antibacterial property than that of AgNO3 
                        [26].

Encouraged by this result, we fabricated a novel ACMCD-Ag/PMMA antibacterial film using a simple solvent casting method. In the SEM images of the thin films as a function of nanocomposite doping amounts (Fig. 7
                        ), the thin film with 0% doping amount appeared to have a flat surface (Fig. 7a), while the other images (Fig. 7b–d) could be seen to have more and more bright white spots with doping content increase, which corresponded to the clusters of ACMCD-Ag nanoparticles. However, when the doping amount reached 4%, the SEM image showed that there existed obvious aggregations (Fig. 7d), so we assumed that 2% is the optimal doping amount. The UV/vis absorption spectra of the thin films as a function of nanocomposite doping amounts are shown in Fig. 8
                        . It could be seen that the absorption band with a maximum at 460nm gradually increased with the doping content increase. By comparison of the results between Figs. 4 and 8, the red-shift of the absorption peak (430nm for the ACMCD-Ag nanocomposite in aqueous solution and 460nm for the nanocomposite in thin films) might be caused by clustering effect of ACMCD-Ag nanocomposite in the thin films [27].
